# Vertical sobel filter
SOBEL_X = np.array([[-1.0, 0.0, 1.0],
                    [-2.0, 0.0, 2.0],
                    [-1.0, 0.0, 1.0]])
# Horizontal sobel filter
SOBEL_Y = - SOBEL_X.T
In [8]:
def gradient_sobel(image, sigma=1):
    image_blurred = gaussian(image, sigma=sigma)
    dx = ndimage.filters.convolve(image_blurred.astype("float"), SOBEL_X)
    dy = ndimage.filters.convolve(image_blurred.astype("float"), SOBEL_Y)
    return dx, dy

Exercice 6¶

Calculez le gradient snapp:

$$ g_{snap} = snap(\frac{\hat{g}}{sin(\frac{\pi}{8})}) $$$$ snap(x) = \begin{cases} -1 \quad si \; x < - 1 \\ 1 \quad si \; x > 1 \\ 0 \quad sinon \end{cases} $$
In [17]:
def snap(array):
    out_array = np.zeros_like(array)
    out_array[array < -1] = -1
    out_array[array > 1] = 1
    return out_array

def snap_gradient(gradient):
    gradient_snap = snap(gradient / np.sin(math.pi / 8))
    return gradient_snap

Extraction de contours¶

Exercice 1¶

En utilisant le code de la section prcdente et le cours, crire une fonction ContoursCanny(image, sigma) qui renvoie une image binaire des maxima du gradient dans la direction du gradient.

In [20]:
def contours_canny(image, sigma=1, threshold=0, padding_mode="symmetric"):
    # Exercise 2
    image_dx, image_dy = gradient_sobel(image_blurred, sigma=sigma)
    # Exercise4
    dimage = gradient_norm(image_dx, image_dy)
    # Exercise 5
    image_dx_norm = np.divide(image_dx, dimage, out=np.zeros_like(image_dx), where=dimage!=0)
    image_dy_norm = np.divide(image_dy, dimage, out=np.zeros_like(image_dx), where=dimage!=0)
    # Exercise 6
    dimage_sx = snap_gradient(image_dx_norm)
    dimage_sy = snap_gradient(image_dy_norm)
    
    # Good practise: name the shape !
    rows, cols = image.shape
    
    # Tip: Pad the image to avoid edges issues
    dimage_padded = np.pad(dimage, pad_width=((1, 1), (1, 1)), mode=padding_mode)
    contours = np.zeros((rows, cols), dtype="bool")
    
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):
            # Get the gradient orientation (dx, dy)
            dx, dy = int(dimage_sx[i, j]), int(dimage_sy[i, j])
            # Get the gradient value
            pixel_grad = dimage[i, j]
            # Get the neighbours i.r.o the gradient orientation
            # Note: x, y != i, j coordinates !
            # Note: don't forget padding indices !
            neighbours = [dimage_padded[i + dy + 1, j - dx + 1], dimage_padded[i - dy + 1, j + dx + 1]]
            # There is a contour if the gradient is above its neighbours
            if pixel_grad > max(neighbours) and abs(pixel_grad) > threshold:
                contours[i, j] = True
            
    return contours

Exercice 6¶

Ecrire une fonction ContoursLaplace(image, sigma) qui renvoie une image binaire des pixels de Lapacien positif qui ont au moins un voisin de Laplacien ngatif.

In [31]:
def contours_laplace(image, gradient=None, sigma=1, threshold=0, padding_mode="symmetric"):
    # Compute the gradient with a Laplacian filter
    dimage = gradient_laplacian(image, sigma=sigma)
    dimage = threshold_gradient(dimage, threshold=threshold)
    # Tip: Pad the image to avoid edges issues
    dimage_padded = np.pad(dimage, pad_width=((1, 1), (1, 1)), mode=padding_mode)
    
    # Good practise: name the shape
    rows, cols = image.shape
    
    # Output contours map
    contours = np.zeros((rows, cols), dtype="bool")
    
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):
            # Get the gradient value
            grad_value = dimage[i, j]
            if grad_value:
                # Get its neighbours
                neighbours = dimage_padded[i:i+3 , j:j+3]
                neighbours_neg = neighbours[neighbours == False]
                # If there are negative values
                if neighbours_neg.size > 0:
                    contours[i, j] = True
                
    return contours

def contours_laplace(image, sigma=1, threshold=0, padding_mode="symmetric"):
    # Compute the gradient with a Laplacian filter
    dimage = gradient_laplacian(image, sigma=sigma)
    # Tip: Pad the image to avoid edges issues
    dimage_padded = np.pad(dimage, pad_width=((1, 1), (1, 1)), mode=padding_mode)
    
    # Good practise: name the shape
    rows, cols = image.shape
    
    # Output contours map
    contours = np.zeros((rows, cols), dtype="bool")
    
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):            
            # Get the gradient value
            grad_value = dimage[i, j]
            
            # Compute the contour for positive gradients
            if grad_value > 0:
                # Get its neighbours
                neighbours = dimage_padded[i:i+3 , j:j+3]
                neighbours_neg = neighbours[neighbours < 0]
                # If there are negative values
                if neighbours_neg.size > 0:
                    grad_diff = grad_value - neighbours_neg.min()
                    if grad_diff > threshold:
                        contours[i, j] = True
                
    return contours

def find_clusters(contours, structure=None, padding_mode="symmetric"):
    # Initialize the first cluster id
    cluster_id = 0
    # Create the structure element, used to tell if a pixel belongs to a cluster
    structure = np.array(structure).astype("int") if structure is not None else np.ones((3, 3), dtype="int")
    assert structure.ndim == 2, f"The rank of the structure element must be 2, got {structure.ndim}"
    
    # Tip: Pad the contour to avoid edges issues
    contours = contours.astype("int")
    pad_rows, pad_cols = structure.shape[0] // 2, structure.shape[1] // 2
    contours_padded = np.pad(contours, pad_width=((pad_rows, pad_rows), (pad_cols, pad_cols)), mode=padding_mode)
    # Binary map used to map clustered pixels and unknown ones
    # Note: also pad this map to avoid edges issues
    clusters_map = np.zeros_like(contours_padded)
    
    # Good practise: name the shape
    rows, cols = contours.shape
    
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):            
            contours_pixel = contours_padded[i+1, j+1]
            # If the pixel belongs to a contour
            if contours_pixel:
                neighbours = clusters_map[i:i+3, j:j+3] * structure
                
                # Get the clusters id from the map (ignore background id i.e. 0)
                clusters_id = neighbours[neighbours > 0]
                # If it's not a new contour, i.e. has neighbours
                if clusters_id.size > 0:
                    # Retrieve the cluster id
                    main_cluster_id = clusters_id.min()
                    # Add the current element
                    clusters_map[i+1, j+1] = main_cluster_id
                    # If two (or more) clusters are connected, merge them
                    if main_cluster_id < cluster_id:
                        for cid in clusters_id:
                            # Merge the clusters on the map
                            clusters_map[clusters_map == cid] = main_cluster_id
                    
                # If it's a new cluster
                else:
                    cluster_id += 1
                    clusters_map[i+1, j+1] = cluster_id
    
    # Optional:
    # Make continuous cluster ids (eg. ids = [1, 3, 6, 12] -> [1, 2, 3, 4])
    clusters_map = clusters_map[1:-1, 1:-1]
    clusters_id = np.unique(clusters_map[clusters_map > 0])
    for i, cluster_id in enumerate(clusters_id):
        clusters_map[clusters_map == cluster_id] = i + 1
    
    return clusters_map, len(clusters_id)

SciPy a dj implment cette fonction, qui se nomme label. J'utilise celle ci pour la suite du TP, car est plus rapide.

In [42]:
# Fast clustering
def find_clusters(contours, structure=None):
    structure = np.array(structure).astype("int") if structure is not None else np.ones((3, 3), dtype="int")
    clusters_map, num_clusters = label(contours, structure)
    return clusters_map, num_clusters

Exercice 2¶

Implmenter une fonction Hyst(contours, gradnorm, seuil) qui produit un nouveau masque de contours avec seulement les clusters ayant au moins un pixel pour lequel le module du gradient est suprieur au seuil.

In [43]:
def hysteresis(contours, gradient, threshold=0, structure=None):
    clusters_map, num_clusters = find_clusters(contours, structure=structure)
    
    assert contours.shape == gradient.shape, "The contours and gradient must have the same shape"
    rows, cols = contours.shape
    out_contours = np.zeros((rows, cols))
    
    # Create a list of contour
    contours_list = [np.where(clusters_map == contour_id, True, False) for contour_id in range(1, num_clusters+1)]
    for contour in contours_list:
        contour_gradient = contour * gradient
        if contour_gradient[contour_gradient > threshold].size > 0:
            out_contours += contour
    
    return out_contours.astype("bool")

def contours_canny_hysteresis(image, sigma=1, threshold_min=0, threshold_max=np.inf, padding_mode="symmetric"):
    image_dx, image_dy = gradient_sobel(image)
    dimage = gradient_norm(image_dx, image_dy)
    contours = contours_canny(image, sigma=sigma, threshold=threshold_min, padding_mode="symmetric")
    contours = hysteresis(contours, dimage, threshold=threshold_max)
    return contours

def contours_laplace_hysteresis(image, sigma=1, threshold_min=0, threshold_max=np.inf, padding_mode="symmetric"):

    contours = contours_laplace(image, sigma=sigma, threshold=threshold_min, padding_mode="symmetric")
